# Project Title: Flight Risk

## Problem Statement
Have you ever had your plans go awry because your flight was unexpectedly canceled? Our nanoGPT model, **Flight Risk**, will calculate the probability of a flight being canceled or delayed so users can plan their trips more accordingly around possible disruptions.

The user is anyone who expects to fly on a commercial airline, as well as anyone whose plans may be impacted by flight delays or cancellations. The problem they experience today is that flights are often canceled or delayed at the last minute, which can disrupt business trips, vacations, and family travel plans.

## Why Now?
AI models now have the ability to use large amounts of data to make more accurate predictions than ever before. This problem matters in the next 3–5 years because air travel demand is high, disruptions are common and costly, and travelers increasingly care about reliability before they book.

At the same time, several changes make this product possible now when it may not have been a few years ago. Aviation data infrastructure is improving, with the FAA modernizing how aeronautical data is collected and shared to support real-time operations, and AI tools are now strong enough to detect patterns across interacting variables such as weather, route history, airport congestion, and airline performance.

## Proposed AI-Powered Solution
Our model gives users insight into the probability of their flight being delayed or canceled. By knowing there is a higher chance of disruption, someone can adjust their plans ahead of time.

For example, a person may agree to pick up their friend from the airport at 10:00 a.m. while also needing to be at work by noon. If that flight gets delayed, that person may have to choose between picking up their friend or going to work. To avoid this problem, the friend could have predicted that there was a high chance of delay and chosen someone with more flexibility in their schedule.

AI and ML add more value than simple rules or heuristics because the reasons flights are delayed continue to change over time. Many delays and cancellations happen because of weather, and climate change is making weather more severe and unpredictable. Because of this, AI is better than fixed heuristics since it can adapt over time as new data becomes available.

## Initial Technical Concept
The first datasets we will use contain information on millions of flights between 2018 and 2022. This includes information such as the date, airline, origin, destination, whether the flight was canceled or diverted, CRS departure time, actual departure time, departure delay minutes, arrival time, arrival delay minutes, air time, CRS elapsed flight time, actual flight time, distance, day of the month, day of the week, operating airline, and more.

We are also adding data to our model that helps predict storms on any day of the year and in any state. For this, we will use another dataset that includes storm date, time, and state information from 1950 to 2015.

Classifier models will be used for this project. The classifier will predict the probability of a flight being:
- On time
- Short delayed (less than 30 minutes)
- Long delayed (more than 30 minutes)
- Canceled

## Scope for MVP
In about 6 weeks, a realistic MVP is a flight reliability ranking tool, not a full booking or real-time disruption platform.

A user can enter an origin, destination, and travel date, and the system returns a ranked list of flight options based on the likelihood of delay or cancellation, using historical on-time performance along with a small set of current factors such as route, airline, departure time, and weather forecast if available.

## Risks and Open Questions
1. **Timely Data:** Past flight data is easier to obtain, but current data is harder to come by. The older the data, the less reliable it may be for modern flight predictions, so this is a potential risk.

2. **Irregular Operations:** Storms, strikes, and other unusual disruptions could make the algorithm less reliable. The AI may be trained mostly on normal operations and may not handle rare events as well.

3. **Changing Operations:** Airlines and airports change their operating patterns over time, so we will need to determine how often the data should be updated to reflect new trends.

## Planned Data Sources
We plan to use Kaggle to source our datasets. We have already downloaded datasets that include thousands of flight records from 2018 to 2022. This data includes information such as cancellation status, delayed departure and arrival times, flight origin and destination, airline, and more.
